# One-hot encoding categorical variables
X = pd.get_dummies(X)

# Split train and test datset
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = model_selection.train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, stratify=y, random_state=117)

# Standardization
scaler = RobustScaler()
scaler.fit(X_train[:])
X_train[:] = scaler.transform(X_train[:])
scaler.fit(X_test[:])
X_test[:] = scaler.transform(X_test[:])
In [11]:
# Define a function to check metrics for each model
def get_metrics(y_test, y_pred, model_name):
    acc = metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    rec = metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
    prec = metrics.precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = metrics.roc_curve(y_test, y_pred)
    auc = metrics.auc(fpr, tpr)
    print(f'{model_name}:')
    print("\tAccuracy Score:", round(acc,3))
    print("\tRecall Score:", round(rec,3))
    print("\tPrecision Score:", round(prec,3))
    print("\tArea Under the Curve:", round(auc,3))
    print("\nConfusion Matrix and ROC Curve:")
    metrics.ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_test, y_pred)
    metrics.RocCurveDisplay.from_predictions(y_test, y_pred)
    
    return acc, rec, prec, auc

3. Compare and Analyze Model Results¶

In [15]:
model_metrics = pd.DataFrame({"Logistic Regression":[lg_acc, lg_rec, lg_prec, lg_auc],
                              "K Nearest Neighbor":[knn_acc, knn_rec, knn_prec, knn_auc],
                              "Random Forest":[rf_acc, rf_rec, rf_prec, rf_auc]}, 
                             index=['Accuracy','Recall','Precision', "AUC"])
model_metrics.round(2)
Out[15]:
Logistic Regression K Nearest Neighbor Random Forest
Accuracy 0.81 0.83 0.86
Recall 0.29 0.41 0.45
Precision 0.56 0.62 0.74
AUC 0.62 0.67 0.71

Based on the model performance metrics table above, Random Forest outstrips Logistic Regression and KNN in terms of accuracy score, recall score, precision score, and AUC. Therefore, undoubtedly, Random Forest should be the best fit to predict customer churn.

Leaving aside the fact that Random Forest has better performance in every metric, when predicting customer churning rate, if the data is randomly sampled, there would naturally be much more negatives (not churn) than positives (churn). Therefore accuracy should not be considered solely. In addition, the business purpose behind the model is to identify customers who are of a higher probability to churn and then perform promotion or advertisement on this specific customer segment in order to lower the overall customer churning rate. It means that we care more about the true positive rate, i.e. recall, since we prefer a customer segment pool in which more churn-likely customers are identified, even though the amount of the pool may be relatively larger.

In [29]:
# Get the Importances and their std for each input variable
importances= rf_model.feature_importances_
std = np.std([tree.feature_importances_ for tree in rf_model.estimators_], axis=0)

# Visualize the Importance information
feature_names = X.columns
plt.figure(figsize=(5,3.5))
forest_importances = pd.Series(importances, index=feature_names)
forest_importances = forest_importances.sort_values(ascending=False)
forest_importances.plot.bar(forest_importances, yerr=std)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.title("Importances of Factors (Random Forest)", y=1.01)
plt.show()

The importance plot indicates that customer age is the most important factor when predicting customer's churning rate. Besides, the estimated salary of the customer, the credit score of the customer, the balance amount in the customer's account, and the number of products the customer purchased are also important.

plt.show()

The mean age of customers who churned is 44.8 while the number is 37.4 for customers who did not churn. The distributions of churned and unchurned customers imply that customers whoes age ranges from 30-40 are less likely to churn while customers whose age is higher than 50 are more likely to churn.
